<h1 class="hero-h">How to write <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">a Claude system prompt.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Most internet advice on writing Claude prompts is either toy-example demos or 14-step "prompt engineering" frameworks for use cases you do not have. This is the real-world version — patterns we use when building Claude Projects for B2B teams, with specifics on what to include and what to leave out.</p>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
<div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;font-size:0.78rem;color:#8FAF8F;">
<div>By <a href="/about" style="color:#F0FFF0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Bill Colbert</a> · <span style="color:#4A6A4A;">Founder, Treetop Growth Strategy</span></div>
<div style="color:#4A6A4A;">Published May 2026 · <a href="/content-library" style="color:#8FAF8F;text-decoration:none;">More from the library</a></div>
</div>
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The 6-part structure</span><h2 class="h2">What every good system prompt includes</h2><ol class="ol"><li><strong>Identity</strong> — who Claude is, in this context. ("You are a B2B proposal writer at [Company].")</li><li><strong>Job</strong> — what task Claude is doing. ("Draft proposals from discovery notes.")</li><li><strong>Audience</strong> — who the output is for. ("Mid-market VPs of Sales evaluating you against 1-2 competitors.")</li><li><strong>Voice &amp; style</strong> — explicit voice instructions, ideally referencing examples in knowledge. ("Direct, evidence-forward, no consultant-speak. Match the voice of the examples in your knowledge.")</li><li><strong>Format</strong> — structure of the output. ("Markdown with sections: Executive Summary, Problem, Approach, Timeline, Investment.")</li><li><strong>Constraints</strong> — what NOT to do. ("Do not invent product features. If you do not know a price, ask.")</li></ol></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Voice instructions</span><h2 class="h2">How to get Claude to sound like your company</h2><p class="body">The single most effective technique: load 5-10 strong examples into the Project's knowledge, and have the system prompt say "Match the voice and structure of the examples in your knowledge." This works better than any amount of adjective-based voice description.</p><p class="body">If you must describe voice in words, be concrete and behavioral: "Use short declarative sentences. Avoid adjectives that praise the reader. Use second person." Beats "Be confident and warm."</p><div class="callout"><p>Voice is shown, not told. Two paragraphs of example output do more than two pages of voice guidelines.</p></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Format instructions</span><h2 class="h2">Getting the shape right</h2><p class="body">Be explicit about format. Specify:</p><ul class="ul"><li>Output type (markdown, plain text, JSON, structured list).</li><li>Section headings exactly.</li><li>Approximate length per section ("3-4 sentences" or "under 100 words").</li><li>Whether to include a TLDR / summary at top.</li><li>Whether to ask clarifying questions before producing output (often yes for complex outputs).</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Constraints</span><h2 class="h2">What to forbid</h2><p class="body">Almost every production prompt benefits from explicit forbiddances. Common ones:</p><ul class="ul"><li>"Do not invent statistics, names, or facts not in your knowledge or the input."</li><li>"If you do not know an answer, say 'I don't know' and ask what to do."</li><li>"Do not use the words [list of words your team hates]."</li><li>"Do not write more than [X] words unless asked."</li><li>"Do not produce output if the input does not contain [required field]."</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Common mistakes</span><h2 class="h2">Why your prompt isn't working</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Identity is too vague.</strong> "You are a helpful assistant" produces helpful-assistant output. "You are a senior B2B sales engineer at a 50-person SaaS company" produces sales-engineer output.</li><li><strong>No examples loaded.</strong> Text instructions plus zero examples = generic output. Add examples to the Project knowledge.</li><li><strong>Conflicting instructions.</strong> "Be concise" + "include all relevant detail" produces medium-length confused output. Pick one.</li><li><strong>Asking for the moon in one prompt.</strong> If you want both research AND drafting AND review, build separate Projects. One Project = one job.</li><li><strong>Forgetting to specify what to do when input is bad.</strong> Without an instruction, Claude will make up missing info. With an instruction ("ask clarifying questions if X is missing"), it will pause.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">A template</span><h2 class="h2">Copy and customize</h2><div class="callout"><p>You are a [role] at [Company], a [one-sentence company description]. Your job is to [specific task]. Your audience is [specific persona], who care about [their priorities]. Match the voice and structure of the example [outputs] in your knowledge — direct, evidence-forward, [adjective specific to your brand]. Output as [format], with sections [list]. Each section should be [length]. Do not [forbidden behavior 1]. Do not [forbidden behavior 2]. If you are missing [critical input], ask for it before producing output.</p></div><p class="body">Replace every bracketed phrase with your specifics. Test with 3-5 real inputs. Refine the prompt based on what fails. Save the working version in your Project. That's it.</p></div></section>

